<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-819-938  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 819 938.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  June 26 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Canada: Epson price-fixing fine found excessive. (Ontario Court ofAppeal cuts fine in half)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Buckler, Grant.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Epson (U.K.) Ltd. (cases).andO;Topic:     Price fixingCourt CasesComputer industry.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>CANADA: EPSON PRICE-FIXING FINE FOUND EXCESSIVE TORONTO, ONTARIO, CANADA,1990 JUN 15 (NB) -- The Ontario Court of Appeal has cut in half a fineimposed on Epson Canada for telling dealers not to advertise the company'sproducts at less than list price.andM;Epson was fined C$200,000 in District Court in December, 1987, forthreatening to cut off supplies of printers and computers to any dealer whoadvertised the products below its suggested retail prices.andP;  It was thelargest fine ever imposed in Canada for such an offence.andP;  The appeal courthas cut the fine to C$100,000.andM;The appeal court's decision gives four reasons for the reduction: Epson didnot know the restrictive clauses in its dealer agreements were illegal, didnot intend harm to dealers or the public, did not make any profit as a resultof the clauses and was unable to control the dealers' advertising anyway.andO;The appeal court decided Epson should be fined C$10,000 each on 10 counts,amounting to a total fine of C$100,000.andP;  Epson had sought a greater reductionof the fine.andM;(Grant Buckler/19900622)</TEXT></DOC>